##The most popular fashion blogger wears a mask to tell fans to pay attention to the new pneumonia

According to the comments on the blog's related tweets, there are still many foreigners who believe that the new coronavirus is no different from the common flu virus and does not require special precautions.

”

New Crown Disease continues to escalate in the global scope, including Italy, South Korea, Iran and other countries, regions have seen a significant increase in the number of confirmed cases. In contrast, well-known people from all walks of life have been speaking out through various channels, calling on the public to raise awareness of the epidemic and the virus.

After a series of events including the cancellation of several brand shows and the confirmation of vips in the front row of fashion week, the fashion industry finally has a heavyweight "opinion leader" to speak out.

Chiara Ferragni, one of the world's most popular fashion bloggers, was the first to post a selfie wearing a protective mask on Instagram, a photo-sharing APP, and urged her fans to be aware of the dangers of the virus, and the importance of protection: "This is by no means a common flu, it's more dangerous for all of us: At this critical moment, stay home as much as possible. And, if you can, tell the people around you to be careful and help the Italian hospitals."

At the same time, she explained the situation in her home country, Italy. She referred to the high number of cases in Italy and the fact that many people were not receiving effective treatment because hospitals were not prepared to deal with the worsening situation. She has therefore launched a crowdfunding campaign to help a hospital in Milan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Italian fashion blogger CHIARA FERRAGNI uses Instagram to alert fans to the new coronavirus

FERRAGNI's Instagram account had about 18.7 million followers on the day it was posted. As of press time, the post has received more than 1.05 million likes. But according to the tweet's comments section, many foreign fans did not respond positively to her appeal. Some see her as a drama queen, insisting it's just another flu; others don't buy the Hoopla of a fashion blogger who obsesses over why she wears eye makeup and dresses in a mask, downplaying concerns about the virus and the outbreak.

In fact, Italy has recently become the country with the most new cases and the fastest-growing epidemic in the world. According to the World Health Organization (WHO) , as of 10:00 a.m. Central European time on March 11,2020,113 countries and regions except China had reported a total of 37,371 confirmed cases, 4,596 new cases and 1,130 deaths. Of these, 977 new cases were confirmed in Italy. March 12, the first Chinese anti-epidemic aid experts flew to Italy to carry out overseas medical assistance.

In addition to threatening public health and affecting the order of normal life and production, the development of different industries has also been more or less impacted.

Italy's fashion industry was hit hard earlier in the epidemic before it reached this level.

Events at Milan's fashion week in late February were affected. Dozens of late buyers and editors were forced to watch Ōhide at a gallery above the Viale Piave show in central Milan after the Dolce & Gabbana show was ordered to be on time by police Giorgio Armani cancelled a live broadcast of the new season's big show and closed its Milan headquarters and factories a few days later.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Outside Giorgio Armani's autumn / Winter 2020 show in Milan

Also cancelling in Milan was American light luxury label Michael Kors. The brand planned to host a press conference and reception in Milan to promote its capsule series with the latest 007 film, no time to die. The Mido glasses trade show, originally scheduled to be held in Milan from February 29 to March 2, has also been postponed. No date has been announced for its re-opening.

Capital markets are also quick to reflect the impact of these shocks. Shares in Italian luxury goods groups fell, with Tod's shares down 11.1% at one point, Salvatore Ferragamo down 9.2% , Safilo down 8.2% and Moncler down at most 5.8% .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Gucci 2020 Autumn and winter show, visible crowd density

Italy is just one example of a global fashion industry that has been hit by the new crown epidemic.

As the global epidemic of new coronary pneumonia continues, Seoul fashion week and Tokyo fashion week, originally scheduled for mid to late March, have been cancelled, while Shanghai fashion week has shifted from offline mode to an online launch in partnership with tmall The launch of the luxury brand holiday series, which was due to start in May, has been called off or postponed by several brands including Gucci, Prada, Hermes and so on In the past two days, the news that Vietnamese socialites who were invited to watch the first-row shows of Gucci and Saint Laurent have been diagnosed with the new coronavirus has further triggered anxiety and panic in the fashion industry about the industry's future.

The global textile and apparel industry will lose more than $1.5 billion due to the outbreak, according to an analysis of the impact of the coronavirus (COVID-19) on global trade released by the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development, the countries in which the companies have suffered losses cover the globe.

Global luxury companies will lose at least $10bn in profits by 2020, according to a new report by Altagamma, an Italian luxury goods association, BCG, a consultancy, and Bernstein, an asset management firm. And the majority of those surveyed expect the global luxury market to be negatively impacted by the outbreak over the next three months to six months.
